Europe's inflation spiked due to food
Accelerated inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant growth in food prices.
November’s price growth in 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, with annual inflation of 3.1 per cent after 2.6 per cent in October, the Union’s statistical office reported.
The official forecast predicted only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian Emissions Bank, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the basic rate of interest, with the reduction, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, leading to the emergence of inflationary spirals.
The ECB would like to keep inflation rates below two percent, but close to them.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to "remove" inflation so that it doesn't have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November’s inflation represents a record of 3.3 per cent for 15 years; in Spain it rose from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the euro area has slumped sharply due to rising food and energy prices.
The term wheat prices have risen by 88 percent, and the soy price has also reached its highest value since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay substantially more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on the world markets rose 52 percent this year, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 per cent in 2008 to 2.5 per cent this year, but will fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation will remain at approximately 3 percent over the next 3-4 months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to double the interest rate during 2008.
