In many places it is saved on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection have been recorded in hospitals, mainly due to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions of hospitals, overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff stopping the infection do not help, says the Primary of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places it is also saved on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatological department of St. John's Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been discovered in a man who got to the hospital after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site at the beginning of the year.
The patient who was injured in a serious car accident was released home, but soon afterwards he had to return home with MRSA infection and because of the bacteria present in his body, one important operation could not be performed.
As of December 10, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been reported in the National Nesocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czov<0xC3><0xA1>, a nurse at the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant causes of the disease have been registered in hospitals with certainty, the others are not known.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin, a resistant gold staphylococcus.
The bacterium Staphylococcus aureus (SA) carries a third of people in the nose without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. heartburn, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if the antibiotics are given excessively or inappropriately, it develops from a bacteria that reacts well to the antibiotics of a bacteria that is very resistant to antibiotics and that spreads quickly under inappropriate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of transient or permanent malfunction of the immune system in patients with a weakened organism, low body weight or in patients over the years can cause serious hospital infections, such as an early infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the top doctor of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections in hospitals belong to daily practice.
"The infection must not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not only there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the originator of the disease is not examined."
Antibiotics and Antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, the nursing staff treats them in rubber gloves and in masks and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients who are admitted to the hospital are examined first whether MRSA is present in their body, however, the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample collection is not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA would be preventable, however, current ratios and conditions in domestic hospitals are not conducive to the prevention of the emergence and spread of multi-resistant pathogens of the disease, says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>z.
Because this infection occurs prominently in hospitals and homes for seniors, hospitals should monitor the patients received and isolate the MRSA carriers immediately.
However, taking microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not in fashion.
This also plays a role in the fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these investigations.
Most cases have been detected in this way if the patient suffers from a noticeable MRSA infection, said the primary epidemiological centre.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, diseases.
It is necessary to make efforts to target antibiotic therapy, or microbiological testing should be carried out to prevent the emergence of resistance to drugs, however, even hospitals do not comply with this in all cases.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in the primary and outpatient treatment of patients, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czov<0xC3><0xA1> said.
Safeguards against disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most often spread among patients through medical personnel.
Therefore, it plays a very important role of hand washing and the use of gloves and masks, but there are also serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by a caprine infection and touch, but in the conditions of domestic hospitals, it is not always possible to isolate infected patients.
On the contrary, rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
As Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czov<0xC3><0xA1> noted, unfortunately, we can also meet with the fact that in hospitals, which are in an unfavorable material situation, it saves on disinfectants, there are few nurses and a lot of patients, so there is a chance of infection.
According to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czov<0xC3><0xA1>, where the necessary protective measures are observed, similar infections are demonstrably less or further spread of the origin of the disease can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it fights against it everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has signed an MRSA prevention program and reduced its incidence.
As it seems, the program is successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England are showing a decreasing trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistance pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these pathogens among its priorities.
