The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernisation of financial markets and, at the same time, enhances investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the individual authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will make it possible to provide financial advisory services to both specialised companies, both natural and legal persons, and will create a new type of financial services provider (ESIS), a financial advisory company (AFI), which will join companies with securities, brokering and brokering companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the performance of operations with financial instruments is expanding by connecting multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets, which will compete with current stock market brokers.
The law further obliges investment firms to market information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk, and ways of coping with risk, and requires a list of all the operations performed to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
