The storm surged in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, second in line to Ben Bernanke, the Fed’s chairman, said that in response to continued pressure on financial markets, executives must be “flexible and pragmatic.”
As part of an apparent effort to calm the irritated markets amid indications of reviving credit efforts, Mr Kohn said the recent excitement “partially reversed some improvements in the functioning of the markets by the end of September and in October.”
He further stated that if increased instability persists, the likelihood of further deterioration in the financial conditions of households and companies will increase.
Investors consider these statements to be a signal that the Fed is ready to deliver additional fresh doses of capital to the U.S. markets, and perhaps further cuts in interest rates to stabilize credit terms.
These remarks also helped calm Wall Street amid further bad news about the U.S. economy when the sale of apartments in October showed record low numbers.
The consequences of financial trust were supported by Bear Stearns’ announcement that it would abolish 650 jobs, which is 4% of its global workforce, as part of a reduction in costs due to the compensation of heavy losses caused by the loss of unearned profits.
Only 20 of these seats are expected to be cancelled in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
